Lecture 3: Point Level Models

Overview of Point Level Models

Visual Motivation

source: airnow.gov

Basic Notation

  • The response, \(Y(\boldsymbol{s})\), is a random variable at location(s) \(\boldsymbol{s}\)
  • \(\boldsymbol{s}\) varies continuously over the space
  • Typically, \(\boldsymbol{s} \in \mathcal{R}^2\) or \(\boldsymbol{s} \in \mathcal{D}\), where \(\mathcal{D} \subset \mathcal{R}^2\), such as Montana.
  • \(Y(\boldsymbol{s})\) is a stochastic process, or a collection of random variables.
  • In spatial settings, \(Y(\boldsymbol{s})\) is referred to as a spatial process.

Conceptual Challenge: Questions

Goals

  • Inference about spatial process \(Y(\boldsymbol{s})\)
  • Create a continous map of air quality, or more generally predict the response at new locations given the partial realization of the process

Discussion Questions

  • What is the dimension of the spatial process, \(Y(\boldsymbol{s})\)?
  • How are predictions made at unsampled locations, and a related question, what does “inference about a spatial process” mean?

Conceptual Challenge: Solutions

Goals

  • Inference about spatial process \(Y(\boldsymbol{s})\)
  • Create a continous map of air quality, or more generally predict the response at new locations given the partial realization of the process

Discussion Questions

  • What is the dimension of the spatial process, \(Y(\boldsymbol{s})\)? It is defined across the entire space, so infinite dimensional.
  • How are predictions made at unsampled locations, and a related question, what does “inference about a spatial process” mean? the spatial process is assumed to have mean (or covariate) properties as well as a specified covariance structure as a function of distance. Similar to a standard regression model, predictions are made using the covariates and covariance.

Spatial Covariance

  • Spatial covariance is characterized by the distance between locations
  • With a structured covariance, few parameters are necessary
  • A covariance function must be symmetric: \(Cov(Y(\boldsymbol{s}_1),Y(\boldsymbol{s}_2)) = Cov(Y(\boldsymbol{s}_2),Y(\boldsymbol{s}_1))\)
  • A common covariance is the exponential covariance, where \[Cov(Y(\boldsymbol{s}_1),Y(\boldsymbol{s}_2)) = \sigma^2 \exp(-\phi d_{12}),\] where \(d_{12}\) is the distance between \(\boldsymbol{s}_1\) and \(\boldsymbol{s}_2\).

Exponential Covariance: Questions

The exponential covariance function has two parameters:

\[Cov(Y(\boldsymbol{s}_1),Y(\boldsymbol{s}_2)) = \sigma^2 \exp(-\phi d_{12}),\]

Describe the how the parameters contribute to the covariance:

  • \(\phi\)
  • \(\sigma^2\)

Exponential Covariance: Solution

The exponential covariance function has two parameters:

\[Cov(Y(\boldsymbol{s}_1),Y(\boldsymbol{s}_2)) = \sigma^2 \exp(-\phi d_{12}),\]

Describe the how the parameters contribute to the covariance:

  • \(\phi\): controls the correlation. In particular, \(\exp(-\phi d_{12})\) will be between 0 and 1 (with \(\phi > 0\) and \(d_{12} \geq 0\)). When \(d_{12} \gg \frac{1}{\phi},\) the correlation goes to zero and When \(d_{12} \ll \frac{1}{\phi},\) the correlation goes to one. \(\frac{1}{\phi}\) is known as the range parameter.
  • \(\sigma^2\): is a scaling parameter associated with the correlation. \(\sigma^2\) is called the partial sill

Joint Distribution

A joint distribution is specified to model the spatial covariance using standard likelihood-based techniques.

  • Let \(\boldsymbol{Y} := \{Y(\boldsymbol{s}_i) \}\) for locations \(\boldsymbol{s_i}, i = 1, \dots, n\)
  • Then assume \[\boldsymbol{Y}|\mu, \boldsymbol{\theta} \sim MVN_n(\mu \boldsymbol{1}_n, \Sigma(\boldsymbol{\theta})),\] where \(\boldsymbol{\theta}\) is a vector of parameters that determine the variance.

Parameter Estimation: Questions

  • Write out the likelihood for \(\boldsymbol{Y}\)
  • Describe the process for estimating the parameters in the model

Parameter Estimation: Solutions

  • Write out the likelihood for \(\boldsymbol{Y}\): \[\boldsymbol{Y}|\mu, \boldsymbol{\theta} = (2 \pi) ^{n/2} |\Sigma(\boldsymbol{\theta})|^{-1/2} \exp\left[-\frac{1}{2}(\boldsymbol{Y} - \boldsymbol{1}\mu)^T \Sigma(\boldsymbol{\theta})^{-1} (\boldsymbol{Y} - \boldsymbol{1}\mu) \right]\]
  • Describe the process for estimating the parameters in the model maximum likelihood for \(\mu\), and \(\boldsymbol{\theta}\) or with Bayesian techniques using prior distributions and Markov Chain Monte Carlo
